;;; prove — the proof solver: offline candidate search, persisted as sidecars.
;;;
;;; The first consumer of the kernel-as-library surface: it imports the
;;; checker toolchain as ordinary modules and drives it IN-PROCESS — no
;;; subprocess. The target module is built ONCE; ONE RunState is threaded
;;; through the run in file order (theory_base_st + theory_step), so the
;;; theory each decl searches against costs only the decls since the
;;; previous one; each candidate is then a direct check_sequent, and only a
;;; WINNER pays a full focused driver pass (the verification). For every `auto` claim/fulfills in the target file it
;;; searches for a proof and persists the winners into the file's
;;; `<file>.auto.shard` via write_file.
;;;
;;; THE SEARCH: every decl tries the flat ladder first — closed-form
;;; candidates, cheapest closer first (refl / compute / simp / arith). If
;;; that fails, two conditional-lemma stages, then structural induction: on
;;; the hinted variable for (auto (induct VAR)), else on each goal
;;; parameter in turn (a hint is an accelerator, not a requirement).
;;; Induction synthesis builds each constructor case's SUBGOAL via the
;;; checker's own build_induct_subgoal and solves each case independently
;;; with a case ladder: per-side unfold/reduce chains over that side's own
;;; fn heads (a file may only unfold fns it owns, which is exactly what a
;;; goal's heads are), optional IH-rewrite tails ((hyp 0)/(hyp 1), lhs or
;;; rhs), closed by refl or a theory backend. The assembled (induct …)
;;; proof is verified WHOLE through the standard driver pass before
;;; persisting.
;;;
;;; The conditional stages (both driven by the checker's OWN RewriteWith
;;; machinery, so what search finds is what replay re-derives):
;;;   - CONDITIONAL CITATION: rewrite the goal with a PREMISED lemma —
;;;     probe the match with apply_rewrite_with_env, require every binder
;;;     bound (no pivots yet), discharge each instantiated premise with a
;;;     mini ladder, close the rewritten goal (refl / arith / a farkas
;;;     cert on the post-rewrite sequent). Candidates carry no insts; the
;;;     checker's capture-match rebinds identically at replay.
;;;   - PREMISE MINING (the lemma-fed have): materialize an instantiated
;;;     linear-fact lemma conclusion as a cut so the farkas side can read
;;;     it (the std/word mod_lo/mod_hi idiom). Match lemma key calls
;;;     against the goal's own farkas atoms, prove the cut by citing the
;;;     lemma, and GROW the fact set monotonically (an added premise never
;;;     hurts — slot 0 ignores it) until the farkas search closes. The
;;;     fact set is SEEDED with promoted hypotheses: every closed linfact
;;;     hyp whose atoms touch the goal's own becomes a trivial have (the
;;;     IH-consuming farkas idiom). Cuts may mention only sequent params —
;;;     which now include NAMED case binders: generated induct cases spell
;;;     their field binders ((case Cons (c0 c1) …)), so facts about a
;;;     case's own fields render. Pin: examples/prove_cond_mine.shard.
;;;
;;; Both terminal stages also fire behind NORMALIZING PREFIXES on a stuck
;;; case: apply (simp both) / rewrite-case-hyps(-then-simp) / unfold+rewrite
;;; chains natively (the checker's own apply_steps) and solve the residual,
;;; persisting (steps (PFX) TERMINAL) — the hand idiom for case-on leaves.
;;; A fulfills' goal is recovered from the target file OR the same-module
;;; mod.req.shard (already in the closure), so module impls get the full
;;; search.
;;;
;;; THE CONTRACT: search happens HERE, offline; `check` only ever REPLAYS
;;; the persisted entries. A solver bug can cost coverage, never soundness —
;;; the sidecar goes through the full untrusted-proof path at check time.
;;;
;;; The sidecar file is MACHINE-OWNED: a rewrite re-renders kept entries
;;; from their parsed form (comments in it are not preserved). An existing
;;; sidecar that does not lex is refused, never clobbered.
;;;
;;; RUN IT:   ./rust_bootstrap/target/release/eval run tools/prove/prove.shard FILE [CLAIM]
;;;           (or `eval direct` — the closure is flat-file imports)
;;;   FILE alone   solve every auto decl that LACKS a sidecar entry
;;;   FILE CLAIM   (re-)solve exactly CLAIM (must be an auto decl in FILE)
;;; exit 0 = nothing left unsolved   1 = some claim resisted the search
;;;      2 = bad usage / unreadable target / unlexable sidecar / module error

(import "../../kernel/stdlib.shard")  ; List / Option / Bool / Pair
(import "../../kernel/loader.shard")  ; World + I/O externs + resolve_closure
(import "../../kernel/driver.shard")  ; check_production + auto helpers + ClaimOutcome
(import "../../kernel/module.shard")  ; Module / TypeDef / type helpers
(import "../../kernel/term.shard")  ; Expr / QName / chars_of_sym
(import "../../kernel/proof.shard")  ; Goal / Equation / Param
(import "../../kernel/types.shard")  ; tc_scrut_targs (the case-on type gate)
(import "../../kernel/arith.shard")  ; farkas_finish / neg_goal_poly (cert search)
(import "../../kernel/admit.shard")  ; ad_sccs — the call-graph SCC partition
(import "../../kernel/checker.shard")  ; check_sequent / build_induct_subgoal
(import "../../kernel/reader.shard")  ; read_all / SExpr / RCtx / build_module_d

;; the explicit library surface this app consumes (STRICT-mode scoping).
(use (:: kernel loader resolve_closure))
(use (:: kernel loader auto_path_of))
(use (:: kernel loader int_list_eq))
